  "prompt": "Does four wheel drive consume more fuel than two wheel drive?",
  "response": "Yes, four-wheel drive (4WD) vehicles generally consume more fuel than two-wheel drive (2WD) vehicles. Here\u2019s why:\n\n1. **Increased Weight**: 4WD systems add weight to the vehicle due to additional components like a transfer case, differentials, and driveshafts. Heavier vehicles require more energy to move, leading to higher fuel consumption.\n\n2. **Mechanical Drag**: The drivetrain in 4WD vehicles creates more mechanical resistance, especially when the system is engaged. This drag increases the engine\u2019s workload, reducing fuel efficiency.\n\n3. **Aerodynamics**: Many 4WD vehicles, such as SUVs and trucks, have larger, boxier designs that are less aerodynamic compared to smaller or more streamlined 2WD vehicles. Poor aerodynamics increases fuel consumption.\n\n4. **Tire Design**: 4WD vehicles often use larger, off-road or all-terrain tires, which have higher rolling resistance and reduce fuel efficiency compared to the tires typically used on 2WD vehicles.\n\n5. **Unnecessary Use**: In 4WD mode, the system distributes power to all four wheels, which is beneficial in off-road or slippery conditions but inefficient on regular roads. Driving in 4WD mode on dry pavement increases fuel consumption unnecessarily.\n\nThat said, modern 4WD systems, especially those with automatic or part-time 4WD, can mitigate some of these inefficiencies by only engaging 4WD when needed. However, even in these cases, 4WD vehicles tend to consume more fuel than their 2WD counterparts overall.",
